# DTO Structure Guidelines

## Base Structure
- All DTOs should extend `AbstractDto` for consistent base functionality
- Use descriptive interfaces for DTO options/configuration
- Implement proper constructor pattern with null checks
- Follow strict typing principles
- **DO use `readonly` for input DTO properties** (as seen in actual implementation)
- **DO NOT use `readonly` for response DTO properties**
- Use definite assignment assertion (`!`) for required fields

## Decorator Usage
```ts
// ✅ Good Input DTO Example
export class UserLoginDto {
  @EmailField()
  readonly email!: string;

  @StringField()
  readonly password!: string;
}

// ✅ Good Response DTO Example
export class UserDto extends AbstractDto {
  @StringFieldOptional({ nullable: true })
  firstName?: string | null;

  @EnumFieldOptional(() => RoleType)
  role?: RoleType;

  @EmailFieldOptional({ nullable: true })
  email?: string | null;

  @ClassField(() => UserSettingsDto)
  settings!: UserSettingsDto;

  constructor(user: UserEntity, options?: UserDtoOptions) {
    super(user);
    this.firstName = user.firstName;
    this.role = user.role;
    this.email = user.email;
    this.settings = user.settings.toDto();
  }
}

// ❌ Bad Example
export class UserDto {
  name: string;
  age: number;
  avatar: any;
}
```

## Field Decorators (Custom Validation + Swagger)
1. **Required Fields**
   - `@StringField({ minLength?: number, maxLength?: number, toLowerCase?: boolean })` - String validation
   - `@NumberField({ min?: number, max?: number, int?: boolean, isPositive?: boolean })` - Number validation
   - `@BooleanField()` - Boolean validation
   - `@DateField()` - Date validation
   - `@EnumField(() => EnumType)` - Enum validation
   - `@ClassField(() => Type)` - Complex object validation
   - `@UUIDField()` - UUID v4 validation
   - `@EmailField()` - Email validation
   - `@PasswordField({ minLength?: number })` - Password validation
   - `@PhoneField()` - Phone number validation
   - `@URLField()` - URL validation

2. **Optional Fields**
   - `@StringFieldOptional({ nullable?: boolean, minLength?: number, maxLength?: number })` - Optional string
   - `@NumberFieldOptional({ nullable?: boolean, min?: number, max?: number })` - Optional number
   - `@DateFieldOptional({ nullable?: boolean })` - Optional date
   - `@ClassFieldOptional(() => Type, { nullable?: boolean })` - Optional objects
   - `@EmailFieldOptional({ nullable?: boolean })` - Optional email
   - `@PhoneFieldOptional({ nullable?: boolean })` - Optional phone
   - `@URLFieldOptional({ nullable?: boolean })` - Optional URL
   - `@UUIDFieldOptional({ nullable?: boolean })` - Optional UUID
   - `@BooleanFieldOptional({ nullable?: boolean })` - Optional boolean
   - `@EnumFieldOptional(() => EnumType, { nullable?: boolean })` - Optional enum

3. **Array Fields**
   - `@StringField({ each: true, minLength?: number, maxLength?: number })` - Array of strings
   - `@ClassField(() => Type, { each: true })` - Array of objects
   - `@EnumField(() => EnumType, { each: true })` - Array of enums
   - `@NumberField({ each: true, min?: number, max?: number })` - Array of numbers

4. **Special Field Types**
   - `@DynamicTranslate()` - For translatable fields (used with translations)
   - Add `{ swagger: false }` to exclude from Swagger documentation

## Constructor Pattern
```ts
export class ExampleDto extends AbstractDto {
  constructor(entity: EntityType | null, options?: IDtoOptions) {
    super(entity);

    if (!entity) {
      return;
    }

    // Required field validation
    invariant(entity.requiredField, 'Required field is missing');

    // Basic field assignments
    this.field = entity.field;

    // Complex object transformation
    this.subObject = entity.subObject?.toDto();

    // Array transformation
    this.items = entity.items?.toDtos();

    // Conditional assignments
    if (entity.optionalField) {
      this.optionalField = entity.optionalField;
    }

    // Translation handling
    if (entity.translations) {
      this.translate(entity.translations);
    }

    // Optional inclusions based on options
    if (options?.includeDetails) {
      this.details = entity.details?.toDtos();
    }
  }
}
```

## Translation Handling
```ts
// ✅ Good Example
@StringField()
@DynamicTranslate()
title!: string;

constructor(entity: Entity | null) {
  super(entity);
  if (!entity) return;

  if (entity.translations) {
    this.translate(entity.translations);
  }
}
// ❌ Bad Example
title!: { [key: string]: string };
```

## Array and Complex Object Handling
```ts
// ✅ Good Example
@ClassFieldOptional(() => ChildDto, { each: true })
children?: ChildDto[];

constructor(entity: Entity | null) {
  super(entity);
  if (!entity) return;

  this.children = entity.children?.toDtos();
}

// ❌ Bad Example
children: any[];
```

## Validation and Invariants
```ts
constructor(entity: Entity | null) {
  super(entity);
  if (!entity) return;

  // Required field validation
  invariant(entity.requiredField, 'Required field validation message');

  // Complex validation
  if (entity.type === 'special') {
    invariant(entity.specialField, 'Special field is required for special type');
  }
}
```

## Best Practices
1. **Naming Conventions**
   - Suffix all DTOs with `Dto`
   - Use descriptive names for option interfaces (e.g., `IUserDtoOptions`)
   - Keep consistent naming between entity fields and DTO fields

2. **Code Organization**
   - Group related DTOs in the same file
   - Order fields logically (required fields first, optional fields later)
   - Keep constructor logic clean and organized

3. **Type Safety**
   - Always use strict typing
   - Avoid using `any` type
   - Properly handle null and undefined cases

4. **Documentation**
   - Document complex transformation logic
   - Add JSDoc comments for non-obvious options
   - Include examples for complex usage scenarios
